{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492432","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492432"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:29:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:29:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1063"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1063","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1063"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.41,0.16,0.12,0.26,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1063"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114731"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1063","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1063"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1063"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96734"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"448"},{"type":"tags","id":"1109"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"898"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14135"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48288"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114731","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114731"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 82-year-old woman presents with a two day history of abdominal pain, distension and obstipation. Two weeks ago she had a right hip arthroplasty and is making a steady recovery. Her medical history includes hypertension and an abdominal hysterectomy. On examination her blood pressure is 140/90 mmHg, pulse 100/min and temperature 37.2 C. Her abdomen is distended, soft and tympanitic to percussion. Digital rectal examination shows an empty rectum. The plain abdominal X-rays are shown (Image 1, 2).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Sigmoid volvulus","Pseudo-obstruction","Paralytic ileus","Caecal volvulus","Small bowel obstruction"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe X-ray shows a considerable volume of intestinal gas. The distended gas loops are large bowel - as identified by their peripheral distribution and the haustral mucosal folds. There is a massively dilated loop of large bowel arising out of the pelvis, with its apex in the right upper quadrant. There is no gas in the rectum. Small bowel obstruction and pseudo-obstruction has a different mucosal pattern, with valvulae conniventes evident across the complete lumen of the bowel.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn this case, the clinical and radiological picture is consistent with a \u003Cstrong\u003Esigmoid volvulus\u003C/strong\u003E. A \u003Cstrong\u003Ecaecal volvulus\u003C/strong\u003E could have a similar pattern of colonic distension - but the dilated loops would be more protruding over on to the left side of the abdominal cavity. The fixed part (base) of the caecal mesentery is in the right side of the abdomen - hence the apex of the volvulus will lean over to the left of the abdominal cavity. Similarly, the fixed section of sigmoid colon mesentery is on the left side of the pelvic rim, with the volvulus thus rising out of the pelvis and veering to the right of the abdominal cavity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWith recent surgery, she may have developed a \u003Cstrong\u003Epseudo-obstruction\u003C/strong\u003E, but this usually occurs within a few days of the surgery itself. In addition, there is usually a more uniform distribution of gas throughout the colon in pseudo-obstruction.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A sigmoid volvulus is manifest by a massively dilated loop of bowel arising out of the pelvis and predominantly occupying the right side of the abdominal cavity."],"references":["Loo JT, Duddalwar V, Chen FK, et al. Abdominal radiograph pearls and pitfalls for the emergency department radiologist: a pictorial review. Abdom Radiol 2017; 42:987-1019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96734"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1063"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18372"},{"type":"media","id":"18373"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18372","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18372"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ab994983-861b-458f-883f-18ea8b992d18.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ab994983-861b-458f-883f-18ea8b992d18.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":716,"height":600}},{"type":"media","id":"18373","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18373"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/2b45e3eb-472b-41f0-92ee-4401bb4fbd45.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/2b45e3eb-472b-41f0-92ee-4401bb4fbd45.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":728,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96734","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96734"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-19T19:43:43+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-19T19:43:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1063"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114731"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"30","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/30"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udff4\u200d\u2620\ufe0f","name":"Radiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-15T15:37:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"he